whmurray@aol.com (WHMurray) writes:

>In article <wild.777607228@access2>, wild@access.digex.net (Steve
>Wildstrom) writes:

>>The security of RSA depends on the difficulty of factoring the modulus, 
>>which would allow you to recover the private key easily. 

>No sir, I am sorry to differ, but it does not.  The work factor for a
>cryptanalytic attack is related to the difficulty of factoring the
>modulus.  However, this work factor is so much greater than the
>alternative costs of obtaining the data that it is hardly related to the
>security.  Rather, the security is a function of many far more mundane
>things.  Phil Zimmerman went to great pains to describe these in the
>documentation for PGP.  (It may not be a masterpiece, but I wish that I
>had written it.)  It is a shame that so few people seem to have read it.

Please pay a little attention to context. The question asked dealt with 
the mathematical difficulty of breaking RSA through factoring. Of course, 
there are a zillion other ways to compromise security, but they weren't 
what the poster was inquiring about.


